#linux #kernel #virtualization

## Initialization

The interrupt controller structure (`kvm_lapic`) is created along with the
virtual cpu in `kvm_arch_vcpu_create`.

Internally, Linux uses the `hrtimer` (High resolution timer) abstraction to
manage virtualized interrupt.

```C
hrtimer_init(&apic->lapic_timer.timer, CLOCK_MONOTONIC,
       HRTIMER_MODE_ABS_HARD);
apic->lapic_timer.timer.function = apic_timer_fn;
if (timer_advance_ns == -1) {
  apic->lapic_timer.timer_advance_ns = LAPIC_TIMER_ADVANCE_NS_INIT;
  lapic_timer_advance_dynamic = true;
} else {
  apic->lapic_timer.timer_advance_ns = timer_advance_ns;
  lapic_timer_advance_dynamic = false;
}
```

Maybe tiemr advance

## Runtime

At the end of `svm_vcpu_run`, there is the call that handle frequent exits.

```c
 return svm_exit_handlers_fastpath(vcpu);
```

## APIC device

`apic_mmio_write`->`kvm_lapic_reg_write`->`apic_update_lvtt`

## Note

### Limiting interrupt frequency

Timer frequency is limited if it is periodic.

```c
static void apic_update_lvtt(struct kvm_lapic *apic)
{
 u32 timer_mode = kvm_lapic_get_reg(apic, APIC_LVTT) &
   apic->lapic_timer.timer_mode_mask;

 if (apic->lapic_timer.timer_mode != timer_mode) {
  if (apic_lvtt_tscdeadline(apic) != (timer_mode ==
    APIC_LVT_TIMER_TSCDEADLINE)) {
   cancel_apic_timer(apic);
   kvm_lapic_set_reg(apic, APIC_TMICT, 0);
   apic->lapic_timer.period = 0;
   apic->lapic_timer.tscdeadline = 0;
  }
  apic->lapic_timer.timer_mode = timer_mode;
  limit_periodic_timer_frequency(apic);
 }
}
```

