#c #programming

While not officially supported, you can implement a kind of manual OOP in C by
playing with type casting and memory layout.

To _inherit_ a struct, you define another type with the inherited as the _first_
member. The children now have the same layout as the parent for begining
objects. This way, the children can safely cast as the parent.

```c
struct parent {};
struct children {
	struct parent parent;
	int a;
	int b;
};

```

A parent object _polymorph_ into the children through `container_of` compiler
macro. This gives additional safety by type-checking if the two type can be
cast.

```c
struct children* c = container_of(parent, struct parent, parent);
```

## KVM example

For instance, the following can be seen in Linux KVM's source.

```c
struct kvm_vcpu {
  // KVM Generic virtual CPU definition that is architectural independent
};

struct vcpu_svm {
  struct kvm_vcpu vcpu;
  // SVM-secific definitions of vcpu, e.g., VMSA and GHCB
};

// Generic x86 interface
static struct kvm_x86_ops svm_x86_ops __initdata = {
    //...
    .vcpu_run = svm_vcpu_run,
    // ...
};

//
static __no_kcsan fastpath_t svm_vcpu_run(struct kvm_vcpu *vcpu) {
  struct vcpu_svm *svm = to_svm(vcpu);
  // SVM-specific implementation using vcpu_svm
}
```

With this pattern, a standard interface for virtualization can be implemented
with the `kvm_vcpu` as argument.

