#programming #cxx

C is known for its type safety issues, so achieving type safety in C may seem
like a crazy idea. However, there are tricks to bring a bit more safety into
your code. For instance, even when the two data representations are identical, a
function can be made so that it expect certain types.

To do this in C, you may retrofit enum and structs. Compiler will generally
raise warning when mismatched `struct`/`enum` types are used. This is very
limited compared to other languages.

## Struct-based

### Generic wrapper struct

This approach implements a runtime-type-like system. It requires more memory for
storing type per struct instances.

```c
typedef struct {
  type_t type;
  unsigned int data;
} wrapper_t;

void foo(wrapper_t data) {
  if (data.type == TYPE_A) {
    /* do something */
  }
}
```

### New struct per variants

This approach just leverage different wrapper struct types to force type safety.

It cannot determine action based on type, but can trigger warnings when
mismatched type is used.

```c
typedef struct {
  unsigned int v;
} type_a;

typedef struct {
  unsigned int v;
} type_b;

void foo(type_a in) { /* DO something*/ }

int main() {
  type_a a = {.v = 50};
  type_b b = {.v = 50};
  foo(a); /* OK */
  foo(b); /* Raise warning */
}
```

## Generic (C11)

G11 provides a `_Generic` keyword
[Generic](https://en.cppreference.com/w/c/language/generic) that can be used to
derive different implementations based on the input types. This requires less
code than the previous struct-baseed implementation. A caveat is that the
compiler must support C11.

```c
typedef enum { A } type_a;
typedef enum { B } type_b;

int foo(type_a data) {}
#define type_safe_foo(input) _Generic(input, type_a: calc(input))

int main() {
  type_a a = 50;
  type_b b = 100;
  type_safe_foo(a); /* OK */
  type_safe_foo(b); /* Raise warning */
}
```

## Reference

- <https://stackoverflow.com/questions/36351496/type-safety-in-c>

